Out[10]:
Text(0.5,1,'People born in different years vs time duration of bike usage')

The above graph represents the data where men ,women , and people of other categories went for bike rides. The number of women who went for bike rides seems to be more than the number of men.

For women in general, majority went for bike rides for almost 20000 seconds.

For men who were born in between 1920-1940, went for bike rides for almost 20000 seconds. For men who were born in the mid 80's and 90's , they went for bike rides for almost 40000 to 60000 seconds. There were women who did go for bike rides for 40000 to 60000 secs. However the numbers are less in comparison to men.

Out[11]:
Text(0.5,1,'Customers vs Suscribers-time')

In the above graph, using a violin plot we have tried to show for how long Customers and Subscribers went for bike rides.

A lot of Male Customers went for bike rides for about 800 seconds. A lot of Female Customers went for bike rides for about 900 seconds.

In the case of subscribers, if you see Male, Female or other gender Subscribers, the violin plot is a little more skewed as compared to Customers, which suggest that there were small number of long bike trips taken by the subscribers.

df_customer = df.query('user_type == "Customer"')

In [20]:
plt.subplot(1, 1, 1)
df_subscriber=df.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
df_heatmap2= df_subscriber.pivot_table(index='day',columns='hour', values='bike_id', aggfunc='count')
sns.heatmap(df_heatmap2)
plt.title('Subscribers hourly and weekly usage')
Out[20]:
Text(0.5,1,'Subscribers hourly and weekly usage')

From the above two heatmaps it is clear that for how many hours on what day Customers and Subscribers took bike rides.

In the case of Subscribers, they took bike rides only on weekdays. Maximum people in them used to travel at around 6, 7 ,8,9 am or at 5, 6, 7 pm.

In the case of Customers, they took bike rides both on weekdays and weekends. On saturdays and Sundays mostly their rides used to range from around 10 am to 4 pm.

Conclusion¶

This project is a win - win situation where a large number of people can benefit from this program:

Environmentally friendly, budget friendly, and lifetsyle friendly.

Subscribers (i.e. daily commuters) benefit from a health commuting choice

Customers (i.e. tourists, students, etc.) have a sustainable, yet flexible option for touring the city.

Good transportation system

There are two types of clients using the system: Subscribers and Customers. Subscribers are primarily daily commuters, having short trips to and from work, who rent a bike on weekdays at 8-9am and 5-6pm. Customers are usually tourists or occassional riders who use the system mainly on weekends to explore the Bay Area. Age is also a factor within user type. Subscribers who fall in the age group between 26-35 years old are the most common age group to use the bike sharing system. The 26-35 years old also lead the spike which occurs across all age groups in October. Subscribers who fall in the 36-45 year old age group are the next most common age group to use the bike sharing system, and follow a similar trend at the 26-35 year olds.
